ering everything about law school from the first day to moot court to job placement to life after law school. Kennedy's book remains one of the most cited works on American legal education.The visually striking original text is reprinted here, making it available to a new generation. The text is buttressed by commentaries by five prominent legal scholars who consider its meaning for today, as well as by an introduction and afterword by the author that describes the context in which Kennedy wrote the book, including a brief history of critical legal studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLawxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 7aLAW / Legal Education.2bisacsh1 aCarrington, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabel, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalley, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaeda, Donna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474778040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814749081.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814749081/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SS